Here's the complete migration from ASP.NET WebForms to ASP.NET Core 8 MVC.

## Pattern Inventory

Your code has **3 patterns** that won't work in .NET 8:

| Line | Pattern | Why it breaks |
|------|---------|---------------|
| `Response.End()` | Request termination via `Thread.Abort` | `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `endResponse=true` triggers `Thread.Abort` | Same â€” no forced thread termination |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow via abort exception | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown in modern .NET |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
// ASP.NET Core 8 â€” ReportController.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    private readonly ILogger<ReportController> _logger;

    public ReportController(ILogger<ReportController> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }

    // Was: btnExport_Click with Response.Write + Response.End()
    // Now: Return a FileContentResult â€” the framework handles headers and
    //      terminates the response. No Thread.Abort needed.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    // Was: btnRedirect_Click with Response.Redirect(url, true) + catch (ThreadAbortException)
    // Now: Return RedirectResult â€” the framework sends the 302 after the
    //      action method returns. No abort, no exception swallowing.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            _logger.LogError(ex, "Request processing failed");
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() { /* ... */ return ""; }
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

**`Response.End()` â†’ `return File(...)`**
In WebForms, `Response.End()` called `Thread.Abort` to halt execution after writing the response body. In ASP.NET Core, returning an `IActionResult` cleanly ends the action â€” the framework writes headers/body for you. No abort needed.

**`Response.Redirect(url, true)` â†’ `return Redirect(url)`**
The `true` (endResponse) parameter caused `Thread.Abort` to prevent any code after the redirect from executing. In ASP.NET Core, `return Redirect(...)` naturally exits the method â€” no forced termination required.

**`catch (ThreadAbortException)` â†’ removed entirely**
This catch block existed solely to swallow the exception that `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw as a side effect. Since `return Redirect(...)` doesn't throw, the block is unnecessary. The general `catch (Exception ex)` still handles real errors.

## Key Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Code after `return` won't run** | In WebForms, code after `Response.Redirect(url, false)` (note: `false`) *would* still execute. With `return Redirect(...)`, nothing after the `return` runs. If you had post-redirect cleanup, move it *before* the return or into middleware. |
| **`Response.End()` in deep call stacks** | If `Response.End()` was used deep in a helper method (not directly in the action), you can't just `return`. Refactor so the helper returns data and the controller returns the `IActionResult`. |
| **Authentication redirect** | The manual `if (!IsAuthenticated) Redirect("/login")` pattern is replaced in ASP.NET Core by the `[Authorize]` attribute + authentication middleware, which handles redirects automatically. Consider using that instead. |
| **Null-reference on `User.Identity`** | `User.Identity` can be `null` in ASP.NET Core if no authentication middleware runs. Use `User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? false`. |
| **File downloads with large data** | For large reports, use `File(stream, ...)` instead of `File(bytes, ...)` to avoid loading everything into memory. |

## Recommended: Use `[Authorize]` Instead of Manual Auth Checks

```csharp
[Authorize]  // Framework redirects unauthenticated users automatically
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult ProcessAction()
{
    try
    {
        ProcessRequest();
        return Redirect("/success");
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        _logger.LogError(ex, "Request processing failed");
        return Redirect("/error");
    }
}
```

Configure in `Program.cs`:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(/* ... */);
builder.Services.AddAuthorization();
// ...
app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();
```

This eliminates the manual auth check entirely and centralizes login redirect configuration.
